h3. Steps to Reproduce:
# Create two issues;
# Create a Scrum (or Kanban) Board;
# Create and start a Sprint;
# Go to the Work mode;
# Select both of the issues created (ctrl/cmd+click);
# Try to move them from one column to the other.

h3. Expected Results:
Both of the issues would be transitioned.

h3. Actual Results:
None of the issues are transitioned. However, moving one at a time works normally, see screenshots below:
|!multiple-issues.png!|
\\
|!single-issue.png!|

Epic name custom field is only available for the Epic issue type. It would be useful to have it available for all the other issue types to perform searches on the issue navigator:

{code:sql}
"Epic Name" = "Epic 1"
{code}

This would retrieve all the issues that are part of Epic 1. The Epic link custom field could provides a similar functionality, however, customers usually link Stories to Epics based on the Epic Name, not the Epic Link. Using the Epic Name for that purpose would make things easier when performing searches in the Issue Navigator.

As of now, it's easy to add an Issue to a Sprint and never realize that it's being blocked by another one. It would be handy if:
- blocked Issues had a notifying icon on their card (as in Classic Boards - GHS-48);
- a note would be displayed then a blocked Issue is added to a Sprint, reminding the user that they might want to resolve the blocking one first.

h3. Issue

When creating an epic and then clicking on the "Create Issue in Epic", a clean new issue is created without associating the issue with the Epic. It seems that the button is working just like "Create a new Issue".

h3. Steps to reproduce

# Create a GreenHopper rapid board;
# In the Epics section (left side of the page), click "Create Epic";
# Create a new Epic;
# Click the dropdown arrow right beside (in the left) the Epic name;
# You will see the number of general issue statistics on this Epic and a "Create issue in epic" link;
# The default "Create Issue" screen will open;
# After creating the issue, you will verify that the issue wasn't associated with the Epic;
# Clicking in the issue to see the detail view will show "Epic: _None_";

h3. Environment clarification

- This is occurring only in GreenHopper 6.2 versions released so far. Versions released before 6.2 (6.1 and below) are working fine.
- This was working before by default (tested in clean instances with GreenHopper 6.1 and 6.0). The correct screen should be called from default;

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *JIRA Software Server*. Using *JIRA Software Cloud*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSWCLOUD-9013].
  {panel}

Opening the Detail View can cause column header text to wrap to multiple lines which can obscure the top of issues if the backlog is tall enough to scroll.

We probably need to call the resize function (which we call on viewport resize) when the Detail View opens/closes.

There has been a couple reports of failed project imports due to incompatible Greenhopper versions between source and destination instances. In the UI it appears that all everything matches up, however taking a closer look in the database, or XML backup, the inconsistencies start to unravel. 

From the XML backup we noticed the following.

application properties section: 
{code}
     com.pyxis.greenhopper.jira:build              : 33
{code}
User plugins section:
{code}
Atlassian GreenHopper                         : com.pyxis.greenhopper.jira
         Version                                       : 6.2.1
{code}

The above looks like the version is 6.2.1. Digging deeper though we find in the same XML backup the version is different:
{code}
<PluginVersion id="10100" name="GreenHopper" key="com.pyxis.greenhopper.jira" version="5.7.4" created="2012-06-22 15:35:34.0"/>
<PluginVersion id="10100" name="GreenHopper" key="com.pyxis.greenhopper.jira" version="5.8.7" created="2012-06-22 15:35:34.0"/>
<PluginVersion id="12001" name="Atlassian GreenHopper" key="com.pyxis.greenhopper.jira" version="6.1.6" created="2013-04-10 09:13:56.11"/>
{code}

Running the following query on the database where the XML was generated from shows the latest version of 6.1.6 as well:
{code}
select * from propertystring where id=(select id from propertyentry where property_key='GreenHopper Version');
{code}

h3. Resolution
- Restarting JIRA appears to update the inconsistent version stored in the database, which should ensure any XML backup generated after that contains consistent version numbers.

KB article: [Incompatible Greenhopper version during project import in JIRA|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRAKB/Incompatible+Greenhopper+version+during+project+import+in+JIRA]
